<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> Curiously, the Portuguese term is the origin of both the Spanish and, via French, the English term, according to <a href="/wiki/Encarta#Encarta_Dictionary" title="Encarta">Microsoft Encarta Dictionary</a>, 2004. It is formed of <i>em</i> ("in", as a <a href="/wiki/Prefix" title="Prefix">prefix</a>), <i>baraço</i> (an old term for "rope") and <a href="/wiki/Suffix" title="Suffix">suffix</a> <i>-ada</i> (which is the feminin form of a verbal ending equivalent to "-ed"), according to its entry in <a href="/wiki/Dicion%C3%A1rio_Houaiss_da_L%C3%ADngua_Portuguesa" title="Dicionário Houaiss da Língua Portuguesa">Houaiss Dictionary</a>.</li>
